vectorData.altText: 3. The group of muscles that form a prominent surface anatomy feature at the base of the thumb is the _______________ muscles.
That's right!  The thenar muscles form the thenar eminence at the base of thumb.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Like the arm, the muscles of the forearm are organized into an anterior (flexor-pronator) compartment and a posterior (extensor-supinator) compartment. Muscles in each compartment share common actions and innervations. 
The deep fascia of the forearm, the antebrachial fascia, surrounds the muscles, deep to the skin and superficial fascia. The anterior and posterior compartments are separated by:
a lateral intermuscular septum that extends between the antebrachial fascia and the radius
the radius
the antebrachial interosseous membrane that joins the radius and ulna, and
the ulna

Muscles of the forearm act at the wrist to cause flexion / extension and abduction / adduction. Other muscles of the forearm send their tendons into the hand to cause flexion / extension of the digits. These are the extrinsic muscles of the hand     .

Intrinsic muscles of the hand     are generally responsible for abduction / adduction of the digits. They include the thenar muscles  which act on the thumb and form the thenar eminence at the base of the thumb.
Muscles with one attachment proximal to the wrist, and one attachment in the hand.
